    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3810413116" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3810413116" />
    <a title="Sookie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4136921-sookie"><img alt="Sookie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599901105p2/4136921.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3810413116?book_show_action=true">May 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sookie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sookie" href="/user/show/4136921-sookie">Sookie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385720373" href="/book/show/108621.In_the_Eye_of_the_Sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4136921-sookie?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4136921-sookie?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4136921-sookie?shelf=2021">2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3810413116" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8983874618881095717">There are very few books that can seamlessly inculcate real life politics into its narration, not be boring, impact the plot and make reader be aware of not just history but contemporary facts as well. <i>In the eye of the Sun</i> takes into consideration the readers are unaware of what is happening, politically, on the streets of Cairo. <br/><br/>The protagonist, Asya, is one of the best characters I have read in recent times. She is an academic, loves humanities and is pursuing her PhD. There is a train of tho</span>
  <span id="freeText8983874618881095717" style="display:none">There are very few books that can seamlessly inculcate real life politics into its narration, not be boring, impact the plot and make reader be aware of not just history but contemporary facts as well. <i>In the eye of the Sun</i> takes into consideration the readers are unaware of what is happening, politically, on the streets of Cairo. <br /><br />The protagonist, Asya, is one of the best characters I have read in recent times. She is an academic, loves humanities and is pursuing her PhD. There is a train of thought that runs across majority of the plot about this and its both aggressively funny and not so at the same time. She falls in love with her husband in increments and the relationship is, odd. And so is the relationship with the British man who comes later in her life. It is in these relationships that we see a different aspect of Asya, a more vulnerable side to her. It is difficult to completely process if what she is feeling in this relationship is fully exposed to the readers, because its clear that her husband isn't invested in their marriage as she is. Her answering silences to his presence (and absence) even when she wasn't happy, was both puzzling and heartbreaking.<br /><br />After not enjoying (at all!) Asya's second relationship, she returns to Egypt (from England) where the story ends. I quite liked the ending, in fact, it had memorable moments that reminded me why I liked Asya as a character and what makes her a strong figure. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8983874618881095717" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


